VALUES
(19, 119, 167, 167, 'kjv', 'hath kept thy testimonies;', 8, 34, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Kept''', 'שָׁמַר (shamar, H8104) - to keep, guard, observe. This Hebrew term conveys not only the idea of obedience but also of protection and preservation of God''s commandments. It implies an active engagement in safeguarding the integrity of God''s law, reflecting a deep commitment to living out His teachings.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8104", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to keep or guard.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 168, 168, 'kjv', 'I have kept thy precepts and thy testimonies: for all my ways are before thee.', 0, 78, 'connection', 'Faithfulness in Obedience', 'This verse resonates with 1 John 2:3-5, which states that knowing God is demonstrated through obedience to His commandments. The connection emphasizes that true love for God is shown through our adherence to His precepts, reinforcing the theme of obedience found throughout Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 John 2:3-5", "description": "Highlights the relationship between knowing God and keeping His commandments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 168, 168, 'kjv', 'thy precepts and thy testimonies', 12, 44, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Precepts''', 'מִצְוָה (mitzvah, H4687) - commandment, law. This Hebrew term emphasizes the authority and importance of God''s commands, suggesting that they are not merely suggestions but divine directives meant for our guidance and benefit.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4687", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for commandment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 168, 168, 'kjv', 'for all my ways are before thee.', 46, 78, 'theology', 'God''s Omniscience', 'This passage suggests that God''s omniscience encompasses all aspects of our lives. Many scholars believe that recognizing God’s awareness of our actions motivates believers to live righteously, as we are always under His watchful eye.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explains the implications of God''s omniscience in our daily lives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 168, 168, 'kjv', 'I have kept thy precepts and thy testimonies', 0, 44, 'question', 'Reflecting on Obedience', 'What does it mean for you to keep God''s precepts in your daily life, and how does that reflect your relationship with Him?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 169, 169, 'kjv', 'Let my cry come near before thee, O Lord', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Seeking God''s Presence', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 61:1, ''Hear my cry, O God; attend unto my prayer.'' Both psalms express an urgent plea for God’s attention and presence in times of distress. The connection highlights the importance of approaching God with sincerity and openness, reinforcing the believer''s reliance on divine understanding and support.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 61:1", "description": "Another expression of urgent prayer for God''s attention."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 169, 169, 'kjv', 'give me understanding according to thy word', 42, 85, 'theology', 'Divine Understanding', 'This request for understanding emphasizes the belief that true wisdom comes from God''s revelation through Scripture. Many scholars believe that this aligns with James 1:5, which encourages believers to seek wisdom from God. It suggests that understanding is not merely intellectual but is rooted in a relationship with God and His teachings.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "Encouragement to seek wisdom from God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 169, 169, 'kjv', 'give me understanding according to thy word', 42, 85, 'greek', 'Understanding in Greek', 'σύννοια (sunnoia, G4920) - understanding, insight. This Greek term conveys a deep comprehension that goes beyond mere knowledge. It emphasizes the importance of both cognitive understanding and spiritual insight as granted by God through His Word.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4920", "description": "Greek term for understanding."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 169, 169, 'kjv', 'Let my cry come near before thee, O Lord', 0, 40, 'question', 'Personal Cry for Help', 'In what areas of your life do you feel the need to cry out to God for understanding? How can this verse inspire you to approach Him with your concerns and seek His guidance in your struggles?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 170, 170, 'kjv', 'Let my supplication come before thee', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Prayer and Supplication', 'This phrase connects with Philippians 4:6, where Paul encourages believers to present their requests to God. Both verses emphasize the importance of bringing our needs before God, suggesting that prayer is vital in our relationship with Him. This demonstrates a deep reliance on God''s provision and guidance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Philippians 4:6", "description": "Encouragement to pray and present requests to God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 170, 170, 'kjv', 'deliver me according to thy word', 38, 70, 'theology', 'God''s Promises of Deliverance', 'This phrase suggests that God''s deliverance is closely tied to His Word. Many scholars believe that God''s promises, as revealed in Scripture, provide assurance of His help in times of trouble. This reflects the broader theological concept of relying on God''s faithfulness and the power of His Word to bring about deliverance.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explains the relationship between God''s Word and His actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 170, 170, 'kjv', 'Let my supplication come before thee', 0, 36, 'question', 'Reflecting on Supplication', 'What does it mean for your supplications to come before God? In what ways can you ensure that your prayers align with His will as revealed in His Word? This reflection invites deeper engagement with the nature of prayer and dependence on God''s understanding.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 170, 170, 'kjv', 'deliver me according to thy word', 38, 70, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Deliver''', 'נָצַל (natsal, H5337) - to deliver, rescue, save. This Hebrew term emphasizes God''s role as a savior who actively rescues His people from distress. Its usage here underscores the psalmist''s trust in God''s power to save based on His promises.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5337", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word meaning ''to deliver''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 171, 171, 'kjv', 'My lips shall utter praise', 0, 26, 'connection', 'Praise in Worship', 'This phrase connects with Hebrews 13:15, which encourages believers to continually offer a sacrifice of praise to God. The act of praising God with our lips is a fundamental aspect of worship, emphasizing the importance of vocalizing our gratitude and reverence. This connection underscores the communal and individual aspects of worship in the believer''s life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 13:15", "description": "This verse encourages the continuous offering of praise."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 171, 171, 'kjv', 'when thou hast taught me thy statutes', 28, 65, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Taught''', 'דָּרַךְ (dāraḵ, H1869) - to tread, to walk. This Hebrew term emphasizes the process of learning through experience and practice. It suggests that the teaching of God''s statutes involves not only intellectual understanding but also the application of those teachings in daily life, reflecting a holistic approach to spiritual education.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1869", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 171, 171, 'kjv', 'My lips shall utter praise', 0, 26, 'theology', 'Role of Praise in Faith', 'Many scholars believe that the act of praising God is not merely a response to His actions but a fundamental expression of faith. This verse suggests that true understanding of God''s statutes leads to authentic praise. It highlights the theological notion that knowledge of God''s Word should naturally overflow into worship, reinforcing the believer''s relationship with God as both teacher and worshipped.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the relationship between knowledge of God''s statutes and praise."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 171, 171, 'kjv', 'when thou hast taught me thy statutes', 28, 65, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Teaching', 'What does it mean for you to have God''s statutes taught to you, and how does this influence your ability to praise Him? Consider how understanding God''s instructions affects your daily life and worship.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 172, 172, 'kjv', 'My tongue shall speak of thy word: for all thy commandments are righteousness.', 0, 78, 'connection', 'Commandments and Righteousness', 'The phrase ''for all thy commandments are righteousness'' connects with Psalm 19:8, which states, ''The statutes of the Lord are right, rejoicing the heart.'' This highlights a consistent biblical theme that God''s laws are not only good but also bring joy and righteousness to those who follow them. Understanding this connection deepens our appreciation for the divine nature of God''s commandments.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 19:8", "description": "Highlights the righteousness of God''s statutes."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 172, 172, 'kjv', 'My tongue shall speak of thy word: for all thy commandments are righteousness.', 0, 78, 'theology', 'Nature of God''s Commandments', 'This verse suggests that the commandments of God reflect His character and moral perfection. Many scholars believe that understanding God''s commandments as inherently righteous helps believers see them as not merely rules to follow, but as expressions of God''s will and nature. This theological view emphasizes the importance of obedience as a response of love and trust in God''s goodness.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 172, 172, 'kjv', 'My tongue shall speak of thy word: for all thy commandments are righteousness.', 0, 78, 'question', 'Speaking of God''s Word', 'What does it mean for your tongue to ''speak of thy word''? How can you incorporate the expression of God’s commandments into your daily conversations and actions? Reflecting on this may reveal opportunities to share the righteousness of God through your own testimony and actions.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 172, 172, 'kjv', 'My tongue shall speak of thy word: for all thy commandments are righteousness.', 0, 78, 'greek', 'Word in Greek', 'λόγος (logos, G3056) - word, reason, discourse. This term ''logos'' is significant as it emphasizes the Word of God as both a spoken message and a living reality, suggesting that speaking of God''s commandments involves engaging with them intellectually and spiritually.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3056", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term ''logos''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 173, 173, 'kjv', 'Let thine hand help me;', 0, 23, 'connection', 'Divine Assistance', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 60:5, where the psalmist asks for God''s help, indicating a dependence on divine support in times of trouble. Additionally, Hebrews 4:16 encourages believers to approach God''s throne for grace and mercy, highlighting the importance of seeking divine intervention. These connections emphasize the believer''s relationship with God as one that is active and reliant on His strength.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 60:5", "description": "A plea for God''s help."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 4:16", "description": "Encouragement to seek grace."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 173, 173, 'kjv', 'for I have chosen thy precepts.', 24, 55, 'theology', 'Choosing God''s Way', 'This verse reflects the theological concept of human agency in the context of divine law. Many scholars believe that God''s precepts are not imposed but chosen by the believer, indicating a relationship characterized by commitment and submission to God''s will. This choice signifies an active pursuit of righteousness and a desire to align one''s life with God''s commands, reinforcing the importance of personal responsibility in faith.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 173, 173, 'kjv', 'Let thine hand help me;', 0, 23, 'question', 'Seeking Divine Help', 'What does it mean to seek God''s hand in our daily struggles? How does acknowledging our need for divine assistance reshape our approach to challenges we face?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 173, 173, 'kjv', 'for I have chosen thy precepts.', 24, 55, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Chosen''', 'בָּחַר (bachar, H977) - to choose, select, or elect. This Hebrew term emphasizes the act of making a deliberate choice, reflecting the believer''s active decision to follow God''s commandments and precepts, illustrating a personal commitment to God''s ways.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H977", "description": "Strong''s number for ''chosen.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 174, 174, 'kjv', 'I have longed for thy salvation, O Lord;', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Longing for Salvation', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 62:1, which states, ''My soul waits in silence for God alone; from Him comes my salvation.'' Both verses express a deep yearning for divine rescue, emphasizing the believer''s dependence on God for salvation. This longing reflects a universal human condition, reminding us of our need for God''s intervention in our lives.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 62:1", "description": "Highlights the theme of waiting on God''s salvation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 174, 174, 'kjv', 'and thy law is my delight.', 41, 67, 'theology', 'Delight in God''s Law', 'This passage suggests that true delight comes from a relationship with God''s commandments. Many scholars believe this aligns with the principle expressed in Matthew 5:18, where Jesus affirms the enduring validity of the law. The delight in God''s law points to a loving obedience that stems from faith, indicating a heart transformed by grace.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 5:18", "description": "Affirms the importance of God''s law in the life of believers."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 174, 174, 'kjv', 'I have longed for thy salvation, O Lord;', 0, 40, 'question', 'Understanding Our Longing', 'What does it mean to truly long for God''s salvation in our daily lives? How can this longing inform our prayers and actions as we seek Him? Reflecting on this question may deepen our understanding of faith and our reliance on God''s grace in moments of need.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 174, 174, 'kjv', 'and thy law is my delight.', 41, 67, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Delight''', 'רֵצֶה (rēṣeh, H7522) - delight, favor, pleasure. This Hebrew term underscores the joy and satisfaction derived from following God''s instructions. The psalmist''s use of this word indicates that the law is not merely a set of rules but a source of profound joy and fulfillment.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7522", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for delight."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 175, 175, 'kjv', 'Let my soul live, and it shall praise thee;', 0, 43, 'theology', 'Life and Praise Connection', 'This phrase highlights a vital theological principle: the relationship between life and worship. Many scholars believe that the act of praising God is an essential expression of spiritual life. The psalmist recognizes that true life is not merely biological existence, but a vibrant relationship with God that is expressed through praise. This reflects the broader biblical theme found in passages like Romans 12:1, where believers are urged to offer their bodies as living sacrifices, holy and pleasing to God.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Romans 12:1", "description": "This verse emphasizes the connection between living and worship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 175, 175, 'kjv', 'and let thy judgments help me.', 44, 74, 'connection', 'Judgments and Assistance', 'The request for God''s judgments to provide help resonates with other scriptural themes, notably in Psalm 19:9, which states that ''the judgments of the Lord are true and righteous altogether.'' This connection underscores the belief that divine guidance is essential for navigating life''s challenges. The psalmist seeks not just knowledge of God''s laws but also their practical application in seeking help amidst struggles.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 19:9", "description": "This verse emphasizes the righteousness and truth of God''s judgments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 175, 175, 'kjv', 'Let my soul live, and it shall praise thee;', 0, 43, 'question', 'Understanding True Life', 'What does it mean for your soul to truly live in the context of praising God? How might your understanding of life change if it is fundamentally linked to worship? Reflecting on this can deepen your appreciation for the act of praising God as not just an obligation but a vital aspect of spiritual vitality.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 175, 175, 'kjv', 'Let my soul live, and it shall praise thee;', 0, 43, 'greek', 'Key Term Insight', 'ψυχή (psychē, G5590) - soul, life, breath. This term refers to the essence of a person, encompassing both physical life and spiritual vitality. In this context, the psalmist expresses a longing for life that is deeply intertwined with the act of praising God, highlighting the holistic nature of existence in relationship with the divine.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5590", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term ''soul''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 176, 176, 'kjv', 'I have gone astray like a lost sheep;', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Lost Sheep Theme', 'This phrase resonates with the parable of the lost sheep in Luke 15:4-7, where the shepherd seeks out one lost sheep, illustrating God''s relentless love and desire to restore those who stray. The connection emphasizes the depth of God''s grace and the importance of repentance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 15:4-7", "description": "Jesus uses the metaphor of a lost sheep to illustrate God''s pursuit of the lost."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 176, 176, 'kjv', 'seek thy servant;', 38, 55, 'theology', 'Divine Seeking', 'This plea for God to ''seek'' the servant reflects the theological theme of God''s active pursuit of humanity. Many scholars believe this aligns with the concept of prevenient grace, where God initiates the relationship with humanity, encouraging believers to seek Him in return.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Henry discusses the nature of God''s grace in seeking the lost."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 119, 176, 176, 'kjv', 'for I do not forget thy commandments.', 56, 93, 'question', 'Commandments and Memory', 'How does the act of remembering God''s commandments influence your daily decisions and actions? Considering the psalmist''s commitment to memory, what practices can you adopt to keep God''s Word at the forefront of your mind?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'In my distress I cried unto the Lord,', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Crying Out in Distress', 'This phrase resonates with Psalm 18:6, which states, ''In my distress I called upon the Lord; to my God I cried for help.'' Both passages underscore the importance of turning to God in times of trouble, highlighting His role as a refuge and source of deliverance. This connection illustrates a consistent biblical theme of reliance on God during crises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 18:6", "description": "Similar theme of calling to God in distress."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'I cried unto the Lord,', 15, 37, 'theology', 'Divine Response to Prayer', 'This passage suggests that God is attentive to the cries of His people. Many scholars believe that this reflects the doctrine of God''s omnipresence and willingness to engage with human suffering. The recognition that God hears our cries reinforces the belief in a personal relationship with Him, where prayer is a vital means of communication.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'In my distress I cried', 0, 22, 'question', 'Understanding Distress', 'What does it mean to experience ''distress'' in a spiritual sense, and how does recognizing this feeling influence our call to God? Reflecting on personal moments of distress can deepen our understanding of God''s faithfulness in response.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'he heard me.', 42, 54, 'greek', 'Hearing in Hebrew', 'שָׁמַע (shama, H8085) - to hear, listen, obey. This Hebrew term emphasizes not just auditory reception, but also the response and action that follows. God''s hearing signifies His attentiveness and willingness to act on behalf of the supplicant.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8085", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''hear.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Deliver my soul, O Lord, from lying lips, and from a deceitful tongue.', 0, 70, 'connection', 'Connection to Proverbs', 'This verse echoes Proverbs 12:22, which states, ''Lying lips are an abomination to the Lord, but those who deal faithfully are His delight.'' Both verses highlight the seriousness of deceit and the divine call for truthfulness. This connection emphasizes the spiritual danger of falsehood and reassures the believer of God''s protection against such threats.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 12:22", "description": "Highlights the contrast between lying and truthfulness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'lying lips', 30, 40, 'theology', 'The Nature of Deceit', 'This phrase points to the theological concept of the sinfulness of speech. Many scholars believe that the Bible portrays speech as a powerful tool for both creation and destruction. In James 3:5-6, the tongue is described as a small member that boasts of great things and can set the course of nature on fire. Thus, this plea for deliverance from lying lips reflects a deep understanding of how harmful words can affect one''s soul and community.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "James 3:5-6", "description": "Discusses the power and danger of the tongue."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'deceitful tongue', 53, 69, 'greek', 'Original Language Insight', 'שָׁקר (sheqer, H8267) - falsehood, deceit. This Hebrew word emphasizes the idea of lying that is intentional and harmful. It captures the essence of deceit not merely as a false statement but as a deliberate act against truth, underscoring the importance of integrity in speech.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8267", "description": "Defines the Hebrew term used for deceit."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Deliver my soul, O Lord, from lying lips, and from a deceitful tongue.', 0, 70, 'question', 'Reflection on Truth', 'Considering the plea for deliverance, how do we discern truth from deception in our lives? What steps can we take to ensure that our own speech reflects honesty and integrity, aligning with God''s desire for truth?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'What shall be given unto thee?', 0, 30, 'connection', 'Divine Justice', 'This phrase echoes the sentiment found in Proverbs 11:21, which states, ''Though hand join in hand, the wicked shall not be unpunished: but the seed of the righteous shall be delivered.'' Both verses reflect a theme of divine justice, suggesting that falsehood and deceit will ultimately face consequences, reinforcing the idea that God hears the cries of the righteous and will respond accordingly.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 11:21", "description": "Illustrates the principle of divine justice."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'what shall be done unto thee, thou false tongue?', 34, 82, 'theology', 'Consequences of Deceit', 'Many scholars believe that this passage highlights the severe consequences that await those who engage in falsehood. The term ''false tongue'' serves as a metaphor for deceit and dishonesty, which are condemned throughout Scripture. This underscores the theological principle that God values truth and justice, and that those who deliberately mislead others will face divine retribution.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary on the Whole Bible", "description": "Discusses the broader implications of deceit in biblical theology."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'What shall be given unto thee?', 0, 30, 'question', 'Reflecting on Justice', 'In light of this verse, how do you understand the concept of justice in your own life? What responsibilities do you have to uphold truth in your words and actions, especially when faced with deceit from others?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'or what shall be done unto thee, thou false tongue?', 31, 82, 'greek', 'Understanding ''False Tongue''', 'שָׁקֶר (sheqer, H8267) - falsehood, deception, or lie. This Hebrew term emphasizes the moral weight of speaking untruths, highlighting that the act of lying is not only a social failing but a spiritual transgression against God’s command for truthfulness.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8267", "description": "Describes the Hebrew term for falsehood used in this context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Sharp arrows of the mighty,', 0, 27, 'connection', 'Biblical Warfare Imagery', 'The phrase ''sharp arrows of the mighty'' resonates with Ephesians 6:16, where Paul refers to the ''fiery darts of the wicked'' in the context of spiritual warfare. This connection highlights the potency of malicious words as weapons that can pierce and harm, much like arrows in battle. Understanding this metaphor enriches our view of the dangers posed by deceitful speech.', 'arrow.triangle.branch', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 6:16", "description": "Illustrates the theme of spiritual warfare."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(19, 120, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'with coals of juniper.', 28, 50, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Coals', 'Many scholars believe that ''coals of juniper'' symbolizes the destructive nature of slander and falsehood. Juniper is known for burning hot and long, suggesting that deceit not only harms its target but also consumes the one who speaks it. This reflects the biblical principle found in Proverbs 18:21, ''Death and life are in the power of the tongue.''', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 18:21", "description": "Highlights the impact of speech."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');